MENTAL MODEL BEFORE YOU START
================================================================================

Think of an agentic AI system as a software entity with agency — it doesn't
just respond, it pursues goals. The key upgrade from a chatbot to an agent is
the addition of: perception, reasoning, action, and feedback loops. This module
is the foundation for everything else in the exam. 15% of the exam lives here,
so this is your highest-ROI study area.

The three tensions you'll see in every scenario question:
  1. Speed vs. Intelligence (reactive vs. deliberative)
  2. Simplicity vs. Capability (single vs. multi-agent)
  3. Autonomy vs. Control (automation vs. human oversight)

Every architectural decision is a trade-off along these three axes.


================================================================================
SECTION 1: WHAT MAKES SOMETHING AN AGENT (Exam Obj 1.1)
================================================================================

Five characteristics — know the definitions and examples cold.

AUTONOMY:
  Operates without constant human direction.
  Example: Customer service agent handles routine inquiries end-to-end.
  Contrast: A chatbot that only responds when prompted — not autonomous.

REACTIVITY:
  Perceives environment and responds to changes in real-time.
  Example: Trading agent reacts to price movements immediately.
  Key: Reactive means triggered by environment, not just user messages.

PROACTIVITY:
  Takes initiative to pursue goals, doesn't just wait for input.
  Example: Research agent proactively gathers information before you ask.
  Key: Goal-driven behavior distinguishes agents from reactive systems.

SOCIAL ABILITY:
  Can interact with other agents AND humans.
  Example: Multi-agent system where agents delegate sub-tasks to each other.
  Key: This is what makes multi-agent coordination possible.

LEARNING / ADAPTABILITY:
  Improves based on experience and feedback.
  Example: Agent refines responses based on user corrections over time.

EXAM TIP: The reactive vs. proactive distinction is a common trap.
  Reactive = responds to stimuli (environment-triggered)
  Proactive = initiates actions toward goals (goal-triggered)
  These are NOT opposites — agents can and should be both.


================================================================================
SECTION 2: THREE CORE ARCHITECTURES (Exam Obj 1.1, 1.2)
================================================================================

This is the #1 most tested topic. Every scenario question comes back to this.

---------------------------------------
2.1 REACTIVE ARCHITECTURE
---------------------------------------
Core idea: Simple stimulus → response. No internal world model, no planning.
Just: "If condition X, do action Y."

How it works:
  Agent perceives environment state → checks rule set → executes matching action.
  No memory of past states beyond what the environment exposes.

Strengths:
  - Very fast (no reasoning overhead)
  - Predictable and deterministic
  - Easy to debug and trace
  - Resource-efficient

Weaknesses:
  - Can't handle novel situations not covered by rules
  - No context — same input always produces same output regardless of history
  - No planning capability
  - Brittle under edge cases

When to use (exam decision rule):
  - Simple, well-defined use cases
  - Latency is the primary constraint
  - Rules are clear and enumerable
  - No multi-step reasoning needed
  Examples: Alert systems, simple FAQ bots, rule-based routing

---------------------------------------
2.2 DELIBERATIVE ARCHITECTURE
---------------------------------------
Core idea: Maintain an internal world model, reason about it, plan actions.
Think "chess engine" — builds a model of the game state, plans ahead.

How it works:
  Perceive → Update world model → Reason against goals → Generate plan →
  Execute plan step-by-step.

Strengths:
  - Handles complex, multi-step tasks
  - Explainable reasoning (you can trace why each decision was made)
  - Goal-oriented — pursues objectives even when path is non-obvious
  - Can anticipate future states

Weaknesses:
  - Slower — reasoning and planning take time
  - Computationally expensive
  - Brittle if world model diverges from reality
  - Struggles with real-time environments

When to use (exam decision rule):
  - Complex multi-step tasks requiring planning
  - Explainability/auditability required (regulatory, compliance)
  - Tasks where getting it right matters more than speed
  Examples: Loan processing, legal analysis, scientific research agents

---------------------------------------
2.3 HYBRID ARCHITECTURE (Production Default)
---------------------------------------
Core idea: Layered — reactive layer handles simple/fast cases, deliberative
layer handles complex cases. Reactive layer routes up when confidence is low.

How it works:
  Input → Reactive layer evaluates → If confidence >= threshold → fast response
  If confidence < threshold → escalate to deliberative layer → reasoned response

Strengths:
  - Best of both: speed for simple tasks, sophistication for complex ones
  - Practical for production: 80% of queries are routine (fast path)
  - Graceful degradation under load
  - More resilient than pure deliberative

Weaknesses:
  - More complex to implement
  - Layer coordination logic must be correct
  - Threshold tuning required

When to use (exam decision rule):
  - This is the DEFAULT production answer for most scenarios
  - Mixed workload (routine + complex queries)
  - Latency SLA required but complex reasoning also needed
  Examples: Customer support agents, enterprise assistants, production chatbots

NVIDIA IMPLEMENTATION:
  Reactive layer: nvidia/llama-3.1-8b-instruct (fast, small model)
  Deliberative layer: nvidia/llama-3.1-70b-instruct (powerful, larger model)
  Threshold: 0.8 confidence score (escalate if < 0.8)

ARCHITECTURE DECISION SHORTCUT FOR EXAM:
  - "Simple, fast, rules" → Reactive
  - "Complex, explainable, regulatory" → Deliberative
  - "Production, mixed load, latency + intelligence" → Hybrid (MOST COMMON ANSWER)


================================================================================
SECTION 3: REACT PATTERN — REASONING + ACTING (Exam Obj 1.2)
================================================================================

ReAct is probably the single most tested concept in the entire exam.
Know it inside and out.

---------------------------------------
3.1 What ReAct Is
---------------------------------------
ReAct = Reasoning + Acting. It's a loop structure, not an architecture.
Can be used inside any architecture (usually deliberative or hybrid).

The four-step loop:
  1. THOUGHT: Agent reasons about what to do ("I need to find X first")
  2. ACTION: Agent calls a tool (search, calculator, API, database)
  3. OBSERVATION: Agent receives result from the tool
  4. REPEAT: Agent reasons about observation, decides next step
     Until: Goal achieved → generate ANSWER

Why it matters:
  - Enables complex, multi-step tasks that need external information
  - Produces traceable, auditable reasoning steps
  - Tool calls are explicit and logged
  - Can recover from errors (observe failure → reason about fix → retry)

---------------------------------------
3.2 ReAct Execution Trace — Memorize This Pattern
---------------------------------------

Thought: I need the population of Tokyo.
Action: Search("Tokyo population")
Observation: Tokyo population is approximately 14 million.

Thought: Now I need to multiply 14 million by 2.
Action: Calculator("14000000 * 2")
Observation: Result: 28000000

Thought: I have all the information needed.
Answer: The population of Tokyo multiplied by 2 is 28,000,000.

Pattern: Thought → Action → Observation (repeats until Answer)

---------------------------------------
3.3 When to Use ReAct (Exam)
---------------------------------------
USE ReAct when:
  - Task requires multiple steps with external info at each step
  - You need explainable reasoning traces (compliance, audit)
  - Actions depend on previous observations
  - Tools need to be orchestrated (search + calculate + verify, etc.)

DON'T USE ReAct when:
  - Single-step query, no tools needed
  - Latency is critical (each loop iteration adds latency)
  - Task is fully self-contained in LLM knowledge

---------------------------------------
3.4 Critical Production Concern: Infinite Loops
---------------------------------------
ReAct agents CAN loop forever — this is a real production risk.
The fix: max_iterations parameter (typically 5-10).

Without limit: agent repeatedly searches for same info, never converges.
With limit: after N iterations, fall back to best available answer.

Also: track previously executed actions to detect cycles.
If same action+params seen twice → break the loop.

EXAM PATTERN: Any scenario mentioning "agent gets stuck" or "loops repeatedly"
→ Answer is: add max_iterations + loop detection.

---------------------------------------
3.5 Four Chain Types Reappear Here
---------------------------------------
(These were covered in Module 4 notes but map to ReAct chain execution)

STUFF: All retrieved context in one prompt → fast, simple, context-limited
MAP_REDUCE: Each doc processed in parallel → scalable for large doc sets
REFINE: Sequential refinement → highest quality, slowest
MAP_RERANK: Score each doc+answer → best for ranked confidence

These apply when ReAct retrieves multiple documents as observations.


