SECTION 4: MULTI-AGENT SYSTEMS (Exam Obj 1.3, 1.5)
================================================================================

---------------------------------------
4.1 When to Go Multi-Agent
---------------------------------------
Single agent is simpler — default to it unless:
  1. Task is decomposable into independent subtasks
  2. Each subtask needs different expertise/model/tools
  3. Subtasks can run in parallel (scaling benefit)
  4. Single agent context window can't hold all task context

If any of those are true AND decomposition is clear → multi-agent.

---------------------------------------
4.2 Three Multi-Agent Patterns — Know All Three
---------------------------------------

PATTERN 1: HIERARCHICAL (Supervisor-Worker) — Most Common in Production
  Structure: Supervisor agent receives task, decomposes, delegates to workers,
    aggregates results, returns final answer.
  Workers: Each specialized (Research Agent, Analysis Agent, Writing Agent)
  Communication: Top-down delegation + bottom-up results

  Strengths:
    - Clear responsibility — supervisor handles coordination
    - Easy to add/remove workers without redesigning system
    - Supervisor can do quality control before returning results
    - Most intuitive for enterprise use cases

  Weaknesses:
    - Supervisor is single point of failure
    - Supervisor bottleneck under high load

  When to use: Most enterprise scenarios — content pipelines, research
    assistants, customer service routing, complex task decomposition.

  IMPLEMENTATION: LangGraph StateGraph with supervisor_node + worker_nodes
    + conditional_edges routing based on supervisor decision.

PATTERN 2: PEER-TO-PEER (Collaborative)
  Structure: Agents communicate directly, no central coordinator.
    Any agent can initiate communication with any other.
  Communication: Bidirectional message passing between agents.

  Strengths:
    - No single point of failure
    - Flexible collaboration patterns
    - Can build consensus across agents

  Weaknesses:
    - Complex to coordinate
    - Conflict resolution is hard
    - Harder to debug and monitor
    - Message loop risk

  When to use: Consensus building, peer review/validation systems,
    distributed problem-solving where no single agent has full context.

PATTERN 3: PIPELINE (Sequential)
  Structure: Fixed sequence of agents, each passes output to the next.
    Agent A → Agent B → Agent C → Output

  Strengths:
    - Simple, predictable, easy to debug
    - Each stage clearly defined
    - Easy to swap individual stages

  Weaknesses:
    - Inflexible — can't skip stages or loop back
    - Bottleneck at slowest stage
    - Error propagation: bad output from Agent A corrupts all downstream

  When to use: Sequential processes where each step builds on previous
    output: ETL pipelines, content generation chains, multi-stage analysis,
    document processing workflows.

PATTERN SELECTION CHEAT SHEET:
  "Different expertise, need coordination" → Hierarchical
  "Need consensus, no clear leader" → Peer-to-Peer
  "Fixed sequential steps, each builds on last" → Pipeline

---------------------------------------
4.3 Agent Communication Mechanisms
---------------------------------------

MESSAGE PASSING:
  Agents send typed messages (request, response, inform) to each other.
  Message has: sender, receiver, content, type, timestamp.
  Asynchronous — sender doesn't wait for response.
  Best for: Loosely coupled agents, peer-to-peer patterns.

SHARED STATE:
  All agents read/write to a common state object (TypedDict in LangGraph).
  State fields are the communication channel.
  Synchronous — agents take turns updating state.
  Best for: Tightly coupled workflows, supervisor-worker in LangGraph.
  This is the LangGraph default: AgentState TypedDict shared across nodes.

BROADCAST:
  One agent sends message to all others simultaneously.
  Best for: Notifications, status updates, consensus proposals.

EXAM TIP: LangGraph uses shared state. Message passing is the protocol for
  loosely coupled multi-agent systems. Know the difference.


