SECTION 5: MEMORY MANAGEMENT (Exam Obj 1.4)
================================================================================

---------------------------------------
5.1 Short-Term Memory (Within Session)
---------------------------------------
Purpose: Maintain conversation context within a single interaction.
Problem it solves: LLMs are stateless — without memory, each message is
  independent and the agent forgets everything you said 5 messages ago.

THREE STRATEGIES:

SLIDING WINDOW:
  Keep the last N messages (e.g., N=10).
  Simple, predictable, bounded memory.
  Problem: Older context is hard-dropped, may lose important early info.
  Best for: Short conversations, FAQ bots, where recent context is all that matters.

TOKEN-BASED TRUNCATION:
  Keep messages until token budget (e.g., 4096 tokens) is exceeded.
  Remove oldest messages when budget exceeded.
  More precise than message count — accounts for varying message lengths.
  Best for: When you have a strict context window budget to manage.

SUMMARIZATION:
  When conversation exceeds threshold (e.g., 10 messages), summarize old
  messages into a compact summary, retain only recent messages + summary.
  Preserves old context in compressed form — nothing is fully lost.
  Requires LLM call to summarize → adds latency and cost.
  Best for: Long conversations (support sessions, research assistants).

WHICH STRATEGY WHEN (Exam Decision):
  Short conversation, simple bot → Sliding Window
  Long conversation, nuanced context → Summarization
  Strict token budget, technical constraints → Token-Based Truncation

---------------------------------------
5.2 Long-Term Memory (Across Sessions)
---------------------------------------
Purpose: Persist knowledge across multiple conversations — personalization,
  learning user preferences, storing facts from past interactions.

VECTOR STORE MEMORY:
  Store conversation turns as embeddings.
  At query time, retrieve semantically relevant memories.
  Implemented with: FAISS (dev), Milvus (prod) + NVIDIA nv-embed-v1.
  Best for: Personalization (remember user preferences, past decisions).

KNOWLEDGE GRAPH MEMORY:
  Store relationships between entities explicitly.
  Example: "User works at TechCorp, manages Bob, is interested in AI."
  Best for: Complex relational knowledge, multi-hop reasoning across facts.

RELATIONAL DB / KEY-VALUE:
  Store structured facts: user_id → {name, preferences, history}.
  Fast retrieval by key, no semantic search.
  Best for: Simple user profiles, session metadata, structured lookups.

MEMORY SELECTION MATRIX:
  Customer support: Short-term = Sliding Window, Long-term = Vector Store
  Research assistant: Short-term = Summarization, Long-term = Knowledge Graph
  Quick Q&A: Short-term = Token Budget, Long-term = None
  Personal assistant: Short-term = Summarization, Long-term = Vector + Graph
  Code assistant: Short-term = Sliding Window (20 msgs), Long-term = Vector Store

---------------------------------------
5.3 Context Window Management — Production Critical
---------------------------------------
Context window = the total tokens the LLM can see at once.
  - GPT-4: 128K tokens
  - LLaMA 3.1 70B: 128K tokens
  - Smaller models: 8K-32K tokens

The challenge: As conversations grow, you'll overflow the context window.
The solution: One of the three short-term strategies above.

Production rule: Always track token count, always have a truncation strategy.
Never let context grow unbounded — it will eventually crash.

Anti-pattern: Unbounded context growth:
  BAD: conversation_history.append(message)  # No limit
  GOOD: if token_count > budget: apply_truncation_strategy()


