SECTION 7: KNOWLEDGE GRAPH INTEGRATION (Exam Obj 1.7)
================================================================================

Knowledge graphs store explicit relationships: entities + edges (relationships).
Example: Alice → works_at → TechCorp, Alice → manages → Bob,
  Bob → works_on → AI Platform, AI Platform → uses → NVIDIA NIM.

WHY KNOWLEDGE GRAPHS IN AGENTS:
  - Relationships are explicit, not inferred — reduces hallucination
  - Multi-hop queries: "Who manages the person working on AI Platform?"
    Answer traversal: AI Platform ← Bob ← Alice (managed by)
  - Provenance: Every fact has a source
  - Consistency: No contradictions — one authoritative answer per fact

WHEN KNOWLEDGE GRAPH > VECTOR STORE:
  - Complex relational queries (multi-hop reasoning)
  - Domain has well-defined entity types and relationship types
  - Consistency and provenance matter (financial, healthcare, compliance)
  - Exact lookups required, not fuzzy similarity

IMPLEMENTATION:
  Neo4j = most common graph DB for agents
  Cypher = query language (SQL equivalent for graphs)
  GraphCypherQAChain = LangChain class that lets LLM generate Cypher from NL
  LLM translates natural language query → Cypher → Neo4j executes → result

HYBRID APPROACH (Best of Both):
  Vector store for unstructured content (documents, text)
  Knowledge graph for structured relationships (entities, facts, org charts)
  Agent uses both: semantic search for context + graph traversal for facts
  This is the production pattern for enterprise AI agents.


