SECTION 8: SCALABILITY AND ADAPTABILITY (Exam Obj 1.8)
================================================================================

HORIZONTAL SCALING:
  Multiple agent instances behind a load balancer.
  Requirement: Agents must be STATELESS (state stored externally).
  External state: Redis, DynamoDB, or a shared DB, not in-memory.
  With NIM: Auto-scaling based on request load, multi-GPU support.

VERTICAL SCALING:
  Optimize per-instance performance.
  TensorRT-LLM: NVIDIA's LLM inference optimizer — up to 10-100x faster.
  Quantization: Reduce model precision (FP16, INT8) — faster inference, less VRAM.
  Caching: Cache common responses — massive throughput gains for repeated queries.
  KV Cache: NVIDIA NIM handles this automatically for inference optimization.

ADAPTABILITY PATTERNS:
  Dynamic tool loading: Register new tools at runtime without restarting agent.
    Example: Agent loaded with finance tools in morning, healthcare tools for
    different client, swapped without code change.

  Learning from feedback: Log user ratings + corrections.
    Accumulate feedback → update system prompt or trigger fine-tuning.
    Don't change behavior after every response — batch feedback analysis.

STATELESSNESS REQUIREMENT FOR SCALE:
  Stateful agents can't be horizontally scaled — each request must hit same
  instance (sticky sessions) which breaks load balancing.
  Solution: Move state to external store (Redis/DynamoDB), make agent stateless.
  NIM enables this by handling inference statelessly.


