SECTION 11: HIGH-PROBABILITY EXAM SCENARIOS WITH REASONING
================================================================================

SCENARIO 1:
Q: Customer support agent, 10,000 req/day, 2-second SLA, 80% routine FAQs,
   needs to escalate complex issues to humans. Best architecture?
A: HYBRID — reactive layer for FAQs (fast path, small model),
   deliberative layer for complex queries, escalation logic.
WHY: 80% fast path keeps latency in budget. Deliberative handles the 20%
   complex cases. Human escalation built into deliberative layer output.

SCENARIO 2:
Q: Agent loops, repeatedly searching for same info. How to fix?
A: Implement max_iterations (e.g., 5) + track action history to detect
   duplicate calls. Break loop and return best available answer.
WHY: Standard ReAct infinite loop prevention.

SCENARIO 3:
Q: Research assistant: gather info, analyze, generate report — sequential.
   Each step needs different expertise. Multi-agent pattern?
A: PIPELINE — fixed sequence, each agent specialized for its step.
WHY: Sequential, no backtracking needed, clear handoff between stages.

SCENARIO 4:
Q: Loan processing agent must verify documents, check credit, calculate risk,
   make approval decision — all explainable for regulators.
A: DELIBERATIVE + REACT — multi-step tool calls (credit check API, doc
   verification), ReAct provides audit trace for regulatory explainability.
WHY: Compliance requires traceable reasoning. Deliberative + ReAct gives that.

SCENARIO 5:
Q: Agent needs to answer "Who manages the person working on the AI Platform?"
   from enterprise org data. Best knowledge approach?
A: KNOWLEDGE GRAPH — multi-hop relational query. Vector store can't traverse
   explicit relationships; graph traversal does this natively.
WHY: Multi-hop relational = knowledge graph.

SCENARIO 6:
Q: Personal assistant needs to remember user preferences across sessions
   (user said they prefer concise answers, works in finance, dislikes jargon).
A: LONG-TERM VECTOR STORE MEMORY — semantic retrieval of relevant preferences
   at query time. Store user facts as embeddings, retrieve relevant ones.
WHY: Cross-session persistence, semantic retrieval, unstructured user facts.

SCENARIO 7:
Q: Agent has very long support conversations that overflow context window.
   Users get frustrated when agent "forgets" what was discussed earlier.
A: SUMMARIZATION MEMORY — summarize old messages into a summary block,
   retain recent messages. Preserves old context without token overflow.
WHY: Long conversations need compression. Sliding window hard-drops old context.
   Summarization preserves semantic content in compressed form.

SCENARIO 8:
Q: You need to scale an agent to handle 100x traffic. What must change?
A: Make agents STATELESS (move session state to Redis/DynamoDB),
   deploy multiple NIM instances behind load balancer,
   enable NIM auto-scaling.
WHY: Stateful agents can't horizontally scale. Stateless design is required.


================================================================================
SECTION 12: ANTI-PATTERNS — WHAT NOT TO DO
================================================================================

OVER-ENGINEERING: Don't use multi-agent when single agent suffices.
  The complexity cost of multi-agent is real. Default to single agent.

UNBOUNDED CONTEXT: Never let conversation history grow without limit.
  Always implement one of the three truncation strategies.

NO ERROR HANDLING: Agents will fail. API calls will fail. Handle gracefully.
  Specific, actionable error messages > generic "An error occurred."

HARDCODED PROMPTS: Prompts should be configurable templates, not string literals.
  Makes tuning, testing, and versioning nearly impossible otherwise.

NO ITERATION LIMIT: Every ReAct agent MUST have max_iterations.
  Infinite loops will burn money and time in production.

NO MONITORING: You can't improve what you don't measure.
  Track: latency, success rate, tool call efficiency, escalation rate.

IGNORING COSTS: LLM calls are expensive. 70B model calls cost 10x more
  than 8B model calls. Route simple queries to small model (hybrid).

SKIPPING GUARDRAILS: Never deploy without NeMo Guardrails or equivalent.
  Every production agent needs input + output safety checks.


